article.description:
Bonzi Wells scored 19 points and Scottie Pippen
added 17 as the Portland Trail Blazers held on for a 108-103
victory over the Boston Celtics on Friday night.
article.headline: Blazers have won nine of last 10
article.linkText: Blazing hot:  Portland continues hot stretch against Celtics
article.story:
BOSTON (AP) -- The Portland Trail Blazers got all they needed from their bench to stay in their winning ways.
 
Patterson
Portland's reserves accounted for 47 points Friday night in a 108-103 victory over the Boston Celtics. With Derek Anderson out with a sprained left ankle and leading scorers Rasheed Wallace and Bonzi Wells in foul trouble, the Blazers still won for the ninth time in 10 games. "Our bench came in and played well," said Wells, who led the Blazers with 19 points. "(Arvydas) Sabonis and Zach (Randolph) came in and got some big rebounds for us." Ruben Patterson scored 15 points and Randolph added 12 points and nine rebounds for the Blazers, while Sabonis carried the Blazers in the fourth quarter, scoring seven of his 11 points during a 13-3 run as they overcame an 89-87 deficit. "He put us on his back there," Blazers head coach Maurice Cheeks said of Sabonis. "When he wanted to score, they didn't have anyone to stop him." Scottie Pippen added 17 points for Portland, which has won six of their last eight against the Celtics, including the last four in Boston. Wallace, limited to 29 minutes due to foul trouble, scored 10 points. "They're a basketball team that can beat you in a number of ways," Celtics coach Jim O'Brien said. "They shot it really well from the perimeter and killed us on the glass. "We could not keep Randolph and company off the glass. He was terrific for them." The Celtics, losers of four of their last five, trailed by 13 points at halftime but, behind Antoine Walker and Paul Pierce, cut the deficit to 83-77 at the end of the third quarter. "We knew they had those two guys and were going to make a run," Wells said. "But, we stayed together as a team and got the win." Shammond Williams hit a 3-pointer to highlight a 12-4 run in the fourth quarter that gave the Celtics an 89-87 lead, their first since the 9:10 mark of the first quarter. Walker had 31 points and 10 rebounds for the Celtics. Pierce added 25 points and Eric Williams and Shammond Williams each scored 14. With Wallace on the bench for much of the first half, the Blazers shot 83 percent (15-of-18) in the first quarter and used a 13-3 run in the second quarter to take a 60-47 halftime lead. Game notes
Blazers guard Antonio Daniels made his first start of the season in place of Anderson. He scored nine points. ... Blazers center Dale Davis, who missed Thursday's practice for unspecified reasons, was in the starting lineup. He was fined $2,500. ... Eric Williams' string of 21 consecutive free throws made, dating to Dec. 18, was snapped with a miss at the 7:55 mark in the first quarter. ... Celtics center Tony Battie missed his second straight game with a swollen right knee. ... Walker picked up his league-leading 14th technical foul; Wallace, who set an NBA record with 41 technicals in 2000-01 and led the league with 27 last season, has four through 31 games.
